01:15.675 --> 01:18.508
-I was 16 when my sister
Kitty was murdered

01:18.578 --> 01:20.045
in New York City.

01:22.015 --> 01:24.711
In an instant she was gone.

01:34.027 --> 01:36.325
No one understood me
like Kitty.

01:42.836 --> 01:44.701
[music continues]

02:03.723 --> 02:05.156
-Two weeks ago today

02:05.225 --> 02:06.715
twenty minutes after 3:00
in the morning

02:06.793 --> 02:08.384
it was a dark night.

02:08.461 --> 02:11.225
Kitty Genovese, 28 years old,
drove her car

02:11.297 --> 02:13.959
into this parking lot
at the Kew Gardens Station

02:14.067 --> 02:16.934
of the Long Island Railroad as
she had been doing for a year.

02:17.036 --> 02:21.029
She stopped, saw a man
against the wall

02:21.107 --> 02:23.473
she didn't quite make it
halfway down the block

02:23.576 --> 02:26.067
before the killer
drove a knife into her.

02:26.146 --> 02:29.172
-I heard the screaming,
and I went to, uh,
the bedroom window

02:29.282 --> 02:32.080
and I saw some girl
on her knees

02:32.152 --> 02:34.347
and she was screaming,
"Help, help."

02:34.454 --> 02:37.150
-Just exactly what was it
you heard?

02:37.257 --> 02:38.747
- "Save me, save me."

02:38.825 --> 02:40.850
-Didn't this frighten you
or shock you?

02:40.960 --> 02:42.723
- No.

02:42.795 --> 02:45.229
- Fifteen years ago, a young
woman was stabbed to death

02:45.298 --> 02:46.788
in front of a Queens,
New York apartment

02:46.900 --> 02:48.868
half a block from her home.

02:48.935 --> 02:50.300
- Tomorrow marks
what many people regard

02:50.403 --> 02:51.870
as one of the most
shameful anniversaries

02:51.938 --> 02:53.428
in New York City history.

02:53.506 --> 02:54.973
-Fifty years ago, her murder

02:55.074 --> 02:57.235
led to the adoption
of the 911 system.

02:57.310 --> 02:59.403
- Police discovered
that more than 30 people

02:59.479 --> 03:00.946
had witnessed her attack

03:01.014 --> 03:02.106
and no one had picked up

03:02.182 --> 03:03.877
the phone to call the police.

03:06.286 --> 03:08.151
[music continues]

03:12.625 --> 03:14.490
-Lights came on
in the apartment building

03:14.594 --> 03:17.722
a window opened, the attacker
got nervous and left

03:17.797 --> 03:20.095
but not a single person
came to the rescue

03:20.166 --> 03:22.600
no one even called
the police at a time

03:22.669 --> 03:26.662
when the average response time
was 2 minutes.

03:26.773 --> 03:29.606
So the man came back
and stabbed her again.

03:33.980 --> 03:36.949
It sent a chilling message
suggesting that we were

03:37.016 --> 03:40.383
each of us,
not simply endangered..

03:40.486 --> 03:42.977
...but fundamentally alone.

03:46.726 --> 03:48.591
[music continues]

04:03.977 --> 04:06.411
-Two weeks after
my sister Kitty's funeral

04:06.479 --> 04:09.312
the "New York Times" published
a front-page story.

04:10.850 --> 04:13.546
It barely mentioned
her killer.

04:13.653 --> 04:16.588
Instead it focused
on Kitty's neighbors

04:16.656 --> 04:19.921
and practically blamed
38 of them for her death.

04:23.763 --> 04:25.856
"The Times" story
was seen as proof

04:25.932 --> 04:28.230
that New York City
was uncaring

04:28.334 --> 04:30.427
that America was
falling apart.

04:31.904 --> 04:33.269
And my sister's been
the symbol

04:33.373 --> 04:36.069
of bystander apathy
for decades.

04:37.677 --> 04:40.009
The girl no one cared about.

04:42.882 --> 04:46.181
But recently "The Times"
published a new article.

04:46.252 --> 04:48.015
It challenged the accuracy

04:48.087 --> 04:50.954
of its original report.

04:51.057 --> 04:54.254
And others now claim
the story of 38 witnesses

04:54.360 --> 04:56.328
is more myth than fact.

04:57.363 --> 04:59.228
[instrumental music]

05:06.372 --> 05:09.364
What did the witnesses
actually see or hear?

05:10.610 --> 05:12.771
Were there really 38?

05:14.714 --> 05:17.080
Why didn't they try
to help my sister?

05:19.218 --> 05:22.483
For years, I avoided
the details of that night

05:22.555 --> 05:24.853
because they were just
too painful

05:24.924 --> 05:27.449
but it's worse
not knowing the truth.

05:38.071 --> 05:39.766
-Mr. Skoller?

05:39.839 --> 05:41.500
- Bill?
-Yeah.

05:41.607 --> 05:43.199
- Hi.
-How you doing?

05:43.276 --> 05:46.074
- Alright. How are you?
Charlie Skoller.

05:46.145 --> 05:47.237
-Bill Genovese.
- How are you, Bill?

05:47.313 --> 05:48.644
-Nice to meet you.

05:48.748 --> 05:49.715
Going around here

05:49.782 --> 05:51.613
is anxiety provoking.

05:51.684 --> 05:52.878
- Are you sure
you wanna do this?

05:52.985 --> 05:53.974
This has to be
very difficult for you.

05:54.087 --> 05:55.520
- No, I absolutely

05:55.588 --> 05:56.782
I absolutely wanna do it.

05:58.658 --> 06:00.421
It's interesting. When you
drive back here it's --

06:00.493 --> 06:02.461
You know, when you're out
on Queens Boulevard there

06:02.528 --> 06:05.656
it seems so,
for me anyway, city-ish.

06:05.765 --> 06:08.859
Here now you're in this really
nice neighborhood.

06:08.935 --> 06:11.768
-This block is
all residential

06:11.838 --> 06:14.534
one-family homes.

06:14.640 --> 06:17.268
Pull into this parking lot.

06:17.343 --> 06:20.835
Because that's where
your sister pulled her car

06:20.947 --> 06:22.938
into this lane.

06:23.015 --> 06:25.142
And this is where

06:25.218 --> 06:27.413
Winston Moseley caught up to her

06:27.520 --> 06:31.786
and struck the first blows
to her back.

06:33.326 --> 06:35.419
Many of your sister's
neighbors

06:35.495 --> 06:37.986
really heard everything
that was going on,
heard the screams

06:38.064 --> 06:40.498
knew that an attack
was taking place

06:40.566 --> 06:43.091
and knew
that it was a violent attack.

06:43.202 --> 06:46.831
It wasn't that your sister
was just screaming and screaming

06:46.906 --> 06:50.034
she was yelling, "Help, help,
I'm being stabbed."

06:50.143 --> 06:53.476
That was not just screams alone.

06:53.546 --> 06:57.539
And Joseph Fink was seated
in the lobby of the Mowbray.

06:57.650 --> 07:00.312
He was the night
elevator operator

07:00.386 --> 07:04.584
and he saw the entire
first attack take place

07:04.690 --> 07:07.955
from beginning to end..

07:08.027 --> 07:11.019
...and he knew exactly
what was happening.

07:11.097 --> 07:13.759
And instead of doing anything,
he got on the elevator

07:13.866 --> 07:16.198
went downstairs,
went to his apartment

07:16.269 --> 07:18.134
and went to sleep.

07:20.072 --> 07:23.235
Now, as she was being attacked
in this hallway

07:23.342 --> 07:25.310
Karl Ross looked down

07:25.378 --> 07:28.870
and he saw
that second attack take place.

07:28.948 --> 07:31.382
And he went to the telephone

07:31.451 --> 07:33.646
called his girlfriend.

07:33.753 --> 07:36.779
She said, "Don't get involved."

07:36.889 --> 07:41.155
- It just kills me to think
that when he first looked down

07:41.227 --> 07:44.094
he could have ended it
right there by doing something.

07:44.197 --> 07:46.324
He could have yelled down, "I'm
calling the police." And that --

07:46.399 --> 07:49.732
-Yes. Or, "The police
are on their way."

07:49.802 --> 07:52.293
- How much time do you think,
if you can remember

07:52.405 --> 07:55.238
from the first attack
to when he finds her again?

07:55.308 --> 07:59.472
- I would say about a half
an hour, possibly 40 minutes.

07:59.579 --> 08:01.945
Long enough for somebody
to have called the police

08:02.048 --> 08:04.243
and for the police
to have arrived

08:04.317 --> 08:07.013
and probably to save
your sister's life.

08:12.658 --> 08:14.523
[instrumental music]

08:47.660 --> 08:49.525
[music continues]

08:51.931 --> 08:53.228
-Turns out,
I'm not the first

08:53.299 --> 08:55.164
to look for these witnesses.

08:57.136 --> 09:00.105
-We traced Karl Ross
to this pet store

09:00.172 --> 09:02.163
but we found that he'd sold it.

09:02.275 --> 09:05.108
The new people here kindly
agreed to contact him for us

09:05.177 --> 09:09.273
but Karl Ross remains silent.

09:09.348 --> 09:11.282
Mr. Koshkin, I wanted
to ask you one more time

09:11.350 --> 09:12.942
if you would speak to us?

09:13.019 --> 09:14.316
-20/20 had no luck

09:14.387 --> 09:17.220
interviewing witnesses
in 1979.

09:19.191 --> 09:20.954
If I was going
to have more success

09:21.027 --> 09:22.494
Charlie Skoller suggested

09:22.562 --> 09:25.497
that I start
with the trial transcript.

09:29.001 --> 09:32.493
My family couldn't bear
to go to the trial in 1964

09:32.572 --> 09:35.700
so I never heard the testimony
of the witnesses.

09:38.711 --> 09:42.374
Only 5 of the 38 witnesses
were called to take the stand.

09:43.583 --> 09:46.347
Samuel Koshkin, Robert Mozer

09:46.419 --> 09:49.411
Sophie Farrar, Andree Picq

09:49.522 --> 09:50.853
Irene Frost.

09:50.923 --> 09:52.788
[dramatic music]

09:58.064 --> 09:59.656
-I heard a shriek.

09:59.732 --> 10:01.893
I got outta bed,
went to the window

10:02.001 --> 10:03.195
and I saw a man and a woman

10:03.269 --> 10:05.032
standing across the street

10:05.104 --> 10:08.403
by the bookstore.
I looked at them for a minute.

10:08.507 --> 10:10.304
Nothin' happened,
so I got back to bed.

10:12.178 --> 10:14.976
The second time she screamed
"Please, help me, God.

10:15.047 --> 10:18.039
Please help me.
I've been stabbed."

10:18.117 --> 10:20.210
I went to the window,
and as I got there

10:20.286 --> 10:21.981
she was kneeling down
on the sidewalk

10:22.088 --> 10:24.522
and he was running
up the street.

10:27.193 --> 10:29.684
-Did you know
Irene Frost at all?

10:29.762 --> 10:31.627
She worked
for your grandfather.

10:31.731 --> 10:33.858
-Oh yeah, oh yeah.
I know the name well.

10:33.933 --> 10:37.369
My grandfather didn't know
much about running
the business

10:37.436 --> 10:39.700
and apparently
I -- Irene stole

10:39.772 --> 10:41.569
several $100,000 from him

10:41.641 --> 10:43.836
so her name
doesn't sit too favorably

10:43.943 --> 10:45.410
in the Hirsch family.

10:45.478 --> 10:46.570
- Now, do you know
if she's alive

10:46.646 --> 10:48.273
or dead at this point?

10:48.381 --> 10:50.246
-Oh, she's long dead.

10:52.318 --> 10:54.183
[instrumental music]

11:02.094 --> 11:05.222
-I saw this girl
at the bookstore kneeling

11:05.297 --> 11:07.822
and this fellow had her down
bending over her.

11:07.933 --> 11:10.766
And I hollered,
"Hey, get out of there."

11:10.836 --> 11:13.600
And he jumped up and ran.

11:13.673 --> 11:16.039
He ran like a scared rabbit.

11:16.142 --> 11:18.474
I never saw anybody
take off as quick.

11:24.016 --> 11:25.881
[music continues]

11:38.664 --> 11:41.326
-I heard the voice upstairs.

11:41.434 --> 11:43.629
Suddenly, the neighbor's
screaming something

11:43.703 --> 11:46.331
and the man ran away
very fast, near the bus stop.

11:47.807 --> 11:50.935
The poor girl get up slowly..

11:51.010 --> 11:53.638
...and she screamed, "Help!"

11:53.713 --> 11:55.578
And walking slowly
toward the drugstore

11:55.681 --> 11:57.308
and up towards
the back street.

11:59.318 --> 12:00.910
I was still at the window

12:00.986 --> 12:03.011
scared, kind of frozen.

12:05.157 --> 12:07.455
And a few minutes
after that man came back

12:07.526 --> 12:10.461
walking normally
as if nothing happened.

12:10.529 --> 12:13.157
And then he went down
to the train station

12:13.232 --> 12:15.097
and then he came out again

12:15.201 --> 12:16.964
and left in the back

12:17.036 --> 12:19.561
and I could not see anything..

12:19.672 --> 12:22.334
...but I heard
the last 2 screams.

12:22.408 --> 12:24.672
"Help, help."

12:24.744 --> 12:26.609
[music continues]

12:54.774 --> 12:56.639
[music continues]

12:59.845 --> 13:03.144
-Hi, is this
the Michael Farrar
from Kew Gardens?

13:03.215 --> 13:05.479
Michael, I just
recently found out

13:05.551 --> 13:09.146
that your mom was with my sister
when she passed away.

13:09.221 --> 13:12.213
I was wondering if she'd be
willing to talk to me?

13:17.296 --> 13:20.288
- My mom, she really
liked Kitty.

13:20.399 --> 13:22.196
And, you know, she can't get
around no more

13:22.268 --> 13:25.465
but I spoke to her
and she told me stuff

13:25.571 --> 13:28.836
that I couldn't hear when I was
younger, what happened and all.

13:28.908 --> 13:31.035
We'll get into that later.

13:40.152 --> 13:41.847
- This was Kitty's
apartment here.

13:41.954 --> 13:44.286
- On this side?
- Right here, yes.

13:44.390 --> 13:45.721
- And then yours
is straight ahead?

13:45.791 --> 13:47.315
- Yes.

13:59.505 --> 14:01.530
This room here,
this was my room.

14:01.640 --> 14:04.666
Kitty's window is right there.

14:07.847 --> 14:09.109
When I went
to school sometimes

14:09.181 --> 14:10.205
if Kitty would have coffee

14:10.316 --> 14:12.841
and toast with my mom.

14:12.952 --> 14:15.147
Kitty confided in her a lot.

14:15.254 --> 14:16.414
They were friends
and they talked

14:16.488 --> 14:17.853
about whatever women

14:17.957 --> 14:19.288
talked about, you know.

14:20.826 --> 14:22.350
-So that night,
what happened?

14:22.461 --> 14:24.292
I mean, in your house,
what happened?

14:24.363 --> 14:27.821
- A -- a scream,
a loud, loud scream

14:27.933 --> 14:31.892
a horrible,
blood curdling scream

14:31.971 --> 14:33.438
and it woke me up.

14:33.505 --> 14:35.871
- How many people
do you think heard it?

14:38.444 --> 14:41.538
- Just looking at the windows,
about 40, 50

14:41.614 --> 14:44.412
could be 60
because it was so loud.

14:44.483 --> 14:47.611
Uh, the whole neighborhood
had to hear it.

14:47.686 --> 14:50.348
And this neighborhood
back in the 60s

14:50.456 --> 14:52.720
I remember
a lot of the older people

14:52.791 --> 14:55.316
they had numbers on their arms

14:55.394 --> 14:58.056
they were
in concentration camps.

14:58.163 --> 15:00.654
That type of a person
might not wanna get involved

15:00.733 --> 15:03.861
with authorities because
of what happened
with the Nazis

15:03.969 --> 15:07.666
so, you know, you can't blame
people for being afraid.

15:07.740 --> 15:11.767
But that night
when I walked up the hallway

15:11.877 --> 15:15.142
my parents were up, out,
this window was open

15:15.214 --> 15:17.910
and my father was looking out
the window.

15:18.017 --> 15:19.348
Well, he didn't see anything

15:19.418 --> 15:21.909
so my parents went back to bed.

15:22.021 --> 15:24.319
About 20 minutes later or so

15:24.390 --> 15:26.415
somebody called my mom

15:26.525 --> 15:30.552
and that's when my mom
said to my father

15:30.663 --> 15:33.996
"Kitty's in the hall bleeding."

15:34.066 --> 15:37.661
And she just grabbed her jacket
and threw it on.

15:37.736 --> 15:39.203
And she started to run

15:39.271 --> 15:41.364
and my father was putting
his pants on

15:41.440 --> 15:43.203
and he says,
"Wait, wait for me."

15:43.275 --> 15:45.140
And she ran down.

15:50.883 --> 15:54.046
- So she comes in, it's 3:30
in the morning or thereabouts

15:54.119 --> 15:55.245
and it's freezing cold.

15:55.354 --> 15:58.050
- It was cold March..

15:58.123 --> 16:00.148
...and this is actually
the doorway.

16:01.961 --> 16:05.920
When my mom tried to open
the door, it hit Kitty

16:06.031 --> 16:09.023
and she was facing her head
towards the door

16:09.101 --> 16:10.728
her feet towards the stairs

16:10.803 --> 16:15.001
and my mother had to push
the door in to get in.

16:15.107 --> 16:17.302
She held her,
and she could feel

16:17.409 --> 16:19.604
the stab wounds in her back

16:19.712 --> 16:23.409
and her hands kept going,
still fighting

16:23.482 --> 16:26.110
and my mom
finally calmed her down

16:26.218 --> 16:29.676
but she couldn't talk
and she started to gurgle.

16:29.755 --> 16:32.280
That was her, she was just
passing then

16:32.391 --> 16:35.360
she was dying, so --

16:36.662 --> 16:40.029
Hours later I opened the door

16:40.132 --> 16:43.795
and the whole bottom
of this foyer was blood.

16:45.004 --> 16:45.993
[instrumental music]

16:49.141 --> 16:52.235
But you could actually
smell the blood.

16:55.147 --> 16:56.944
You know, it's like something
you don't forget.

16:57.016 --> 16:59.041
It's like walking
in an old butcher shop

16:59.151 --> 17:02.643
how you could smell that
the -- the human, the meat.

17:02.755 --> 17:04.746
It -- You know, it --

17:07.593 --> 17:11.461
The prints on the wall
were marked in pencil

17:11.530 --> 17:13.896
1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

17:13.999 --> 17:15.694
And it wasn't until
I was talking to my mother

17:15.800 --> 17:19.567
and I said when I looked in,
I saw the handprint.

17:19.637 --> 17:23.233
And she says, "That was
my fingerprints on the wall."

17:23.308 --> 17:24.638
- Your mom?
-Yeah.

17:24.710 --> 17:27.076
'Cause when she went
to get up, she was like

17:27.179 --> 17:30.945
she went and she put her hands
on the wall.

17:31.016 --> 17:35.510
My mom spoke to one woman
from a newspaper back then

17:35.621 --> 17:38.112
and she told her what happened
and the woman says

17:38.190 --> 17:39.953
you know, "Would you do that
again, if you had to? "

17:40.025 --> 17:42.016
And my mother says,
"Certainly, of course."

17:42.127 --> 17:44.152
When the paper come out,
it says my mom said

17:44.229 --> 17:45.924
that she would never get
involved with it

17:46.031 --> 17:48.226
and that's when my mother says,
"lt don't pay to talk

17:48.333 --> 17:50.324
because they twist
what you say."

17:50.402 --> 17:54.429
And that's, she never said
anything since...you know.

17:54.540 --> 17:56.974
- Do you think your mother
would talk to me?

17:57.042 --> 18:00.011
- I -- I'll twist her arm
a little, you know,
but I think she would.

18:00.079 --> 18:01.444
- Not, not too hard, but --

18:01.547 --> 18:04.141
- I think that she would
do that.

18:04.216 --> 18:05.183
- Thank you so much.

18:05.250 --> 18:06.239
- I wish it could have been

18:06.351 --> 18:07.318
different circumstances.

18:07.386 --> 18:08.876
Alright?
- Yeah, really.

18:08.987 --> 18:11.922
- You know, give the best
to your family and --

18:15.027 --> 18:16.892
[music continues]

18:26.238 --> 18:29.366
-Why was Sophia left out
of the original story?

18:34.446 --> 18:37.540
It would have made such
a difference to my family

18:37.616 --> 18:40.244
knowing that Kitty died
in the arms of a friend.

18:43.956 --> 18:47.119
Truth is my family
doesn't know much
about Kitty's murder.

18:50.362 --> 18:53.024
The only time we learned
any details of that night

18:53.098 --> 18:54.895
was in 1995.

18:54.967 --> 18:58.130
That's when the killer
appealed for a retrial.

19:01.440 --> 19:03.601
It briefly brought us
face to face with the man

19:03.709 --> 19:06.337
who murdered and attempted
to rape Kitty.

19:09.481 --> 19:11.312
Hearing those details
for the first time

19:11.416 --> 19:14.283
was unbearable for me
and my siblings.

19:17.789 --> 19:19.222
- Speaking for myself..

19:21.493 --> 19:22.926
[sighs]

19:22.995 --> 19:25.088
...it never goes away.

19:28.300 --> 19:31.497
I never forget the day

19:31.603 --> 19:33.798
that the policemen
in New Canaan

19:33.906 --> 19:37.239
came to our door,
knocked on it..

19:37.309 --> 19:38.742
...and told us what happened.

19:38.810 --> 19:40.402
- It was very early
in the morning

19:40.479 --> 19:41.946
and the doorbell went off

19:42.014 --> 19:43.709
and I think
I was awakened by that

19:43.815 --> 19:46.682
and I heard
the -- the conversations.

19:46.785 --> 19:48.218
And then, then, then

19:48.287 --> 19:51.450
just ex -- extreme

19:51.523 --> 19:54.515
like piercing, screaming.

19:54.626 --> 19:57.094
And then freezing in my bed.

19:58.931 --> 20:01.900
-My mother, my mother
was a basket case.

20:01.967 --> 20:05.425
My father was also.

20:05.504 --> 20:08.803
My father couldn't even
identify my, my, uh

20:08.874 --> 20:12.310
sister's body in the morgue. He
had to send his brother there.

20:12.377 --> 20:13.742
- And the neighbors
are all like

20:13.845 --> 20:16.541
"Oh, my God,
what can we do for you? "

20:16.648 --> 20:19.481
And it's like, uh --

20:19.551 --> 20:22.213
"Why don't you take,
why don't you take Frank? "

20:22.321 --> 20:24.619
I -- I just went off
to the McSweeny's.

20:25.791 --> 20:27.588
I was with them for weeks.

20:29.161 --> 20:32.324
I never even went
to my sister's funeral.

20:35.000 --> 20:38.595
It was all over the news,
everywhere.

20:38.670 --> 20:40.934
So, I got a lot
of my information

20:41.006 --> 20:44.806
just from sneaking maybe,
and turning on a TV and --

20:47.980 --> 20:51.848
-The only thing we could
think about is the tragedy.

20:51.917 --> 20:55.614
We almost erased her
from our lives.

20:57.189 --> 20:59.054
[instrumental music]

21:01.260 --> 21:04.787
Bill, it's hard to say
how he handled it.

21:04.896 --> 21:07.387
I -- I -- I really, you know,
we really never sat down

21:07.499 --> 21:10.798
and talked about it.

21:10.869 --> 21:13.963
She took a --
a shine to Billy.

21:18.010 --> 21:20.478
She spent a lot of time
with him.

21:31.189 --> 21:33.987
-Kitty and I were separated
when I was 6.

21:35.927 --> 21:37.554
That year my parents decided

21:37.629 --> 21:39.494
the city
was getting too dangerous

21:39.598 --> 21:41.862
so we left
for New Canaan, Connecticut.

21:44.303 --> 21:46.669
Kitty had already
graduated high school

21:46.772 --> 21:48.706
and much to my parent's
frustration

21:48.774 --> 21:50.742
she decided
to stay in the city.

21:52.944 --> 21:55.777
For the next 10 years,
I only saw her on weekends

21:55.881 --> 21:57.143
when she would come to visit.

21:59.117 --> 22:02.644
We'd have a lot of fun driving
around in her red Fiat.

22:06.825 --> 22:09.157
But the best part was talking
late into the night.

22:10.829 --> 22:14.595
Kitty seemed to know
about everything.

22:14.666 --> 22:17.362
And I was a curious kid
and asked a lot of questions.

22:19.404 --> 22:21.565
Kitty always took the time
to answer them.

22:43.628 --> 22:47.257
For decades, the identity
of the so called 38 witnesses

22:47.332 --> 22:49.357
has been a mystery.

22:49.468 --> 22:51.629
If I was going to track
any of them down

22:51.703 --> 22:55.503
first I'd have to find out
who they were.

22:55.607 --> 22:58.599
I requested
all the information
on my sister's murder

22:58.677 --> 23:02.010
from the New York police
department.

23:02.114 --> 23:04.708
They sent me copies
of the original detective

23:04.783 --> 23:08.116
accounts of witness interviews
called DD5's.

23:10.155 --> 23:12.953
-I saw her, she was wearing
a black coat and high heels

23:13.024 --> 23:15.322
and the coat was held
around her body.

23:15.394 --> 23:18.659
She was a, a small girl --
-Terrific scream.

23:18.730 --> 23:21.426
-What I thought at first
was some cat --

23:21.533 --> 23:24.866
-It sounded like a child.

23:24.970 --> 23:29.464
-And I looked out to see
and I couldn't see anything.
-Otherwise I --

23:29.541 --> 23:32.135
-The police want to know
your name and everything
and they get people involved.

23:32.210 --> 23:34.405
These kind of people don't
want to get involved.
-Why didn't we do something?

23:34.513 --> 23:36.708
-I mean, I -- I feel
a terrible guilt.

23:40.819 --> 23:43.413
-Much of the reports
were illegible.

23:43.488 --> 23:46.082
And almost all the names
had been redacted.

23:50.362 --> 23:54.196
I was at a dead end
without the names.

23:54.266 --> 23:56.962
But I thought of someone
who might be able to help.

23:57.068 --> 23:59.263
- 20/20 has gone back
to reexamine

23:59.371 --> 24:00.861
what has become
a classic case

24:00.939 --> 24:03.305
not of crime,
but of social behavior.

24:03.408 --> 24:04.773
-Hello?
-Aram?

24:04.876 --> 24:06.707
-Yes.
-This is Bill Genovese.

24:06.778 --> 24:08.541
My sister was Kitty Genovese.

24:08.613 --> 24:10.706
-Oh, yes.
Oh, my goodness.

24:10.782 --> 24:14.479
- Did you, did you have any
luck in reaching
any of the witnesses?

24:14.586 --> 24:16.747
-I did try
to track them down, yes.

24:16.855 --> 24:18.823
I used to have a file.

24:18.890 --> 24:21.085
Uh, I have some stuff
at Columbia

24:21.193 --> 24:23.525
and, uh, if it were anywhere

24:23.595 --> 24:25.085
it could be there.

24:26.431 --> 24:28.296
[instrumental music]

24:30.302 --> 24:31.735
-The list Aram had found

24:31.803 --> 24:33.168
contained summarized versions

24:33.271 --> 24:35.865
of the witness accounts.

24:35.941 --> 24:39.741
Most importantly,
it had the names.

24:39.811 --> 24:41.642
These statements
from the neighbors

24:41.746 --> 24:44.442
matched the DD5 reports.

24:44.549 --> 24:48.041
So Aram's list must have come
from the police interviews.

24:49.788 --> 24:51.221
When I added up the number

24:51.289 --> 24:53.086
of entries, there were 38.

24:54.793 --> 24:56.886
Could these be
the 38 witnesses?

24:58.930 --> 25:00.795
[music continues]

25:08.006 --> 25:09.871
[dogs barking]

25:15.947 --> 25:18.575
Lynne, I presume.
- Yes, Bill, I presume.

25:18.650 --> 25:21.847
-Yes, and you're Tod.
- This is Tod. Bill.

25:21.953 --> 25:23.887
- Uh, Bill.
-How're you doing?

25:23.955 --> 25:25.718
- Good.
Can I help?

25:25.790 --> 25:27.758
- Nah, I'm good.
- Okay.

25:30.595 --> 25:31.584
- Can't we help you?

25:31.663 --> 25:33.130
- Over here, yeah.

25:34.799 --> 25:36.790
So, you lived
in the Mowbray?

25:36.868 --> 25:38.495
What apartment, what floor?

25:38.603 --> 25:42.232
- Second floor. 214.

25:42.307 --> 25:44.138
- Did you feel
like the neighborhood was safe?

25:44.209 --> 25:45.198
- Yes.

25:45.310 --> 25:46.937
- Cause you were 19, 20

25:47.012 --> 25:48.673
around 1964.

25:48.780 --> 25:51.271
Did you feel you could come
and go in the evening?

25:51.349 --> 25:55.012
- Oh, yes,
but I could see people

25:55.120 --> 25:57.611
and they would just pull down
the shades or --

25:57.689 --> 25:59.316
There was a fear.

25:59.391 --> 26:02.883
There was a fear
in that building, I think.

26:02.994 --> 26:04.859
-What was your experience
that night?

26:04.963 --> 26:07.329
- I heard a scream.
It woke me up.

26:07.399 --> 26:09.890
I looked out the window,
I didn't see anything

26:10.001 --> 26:11.628
I didn't hear any more.

26:11.703 --> 26:14.399
And I said, "Oh, well."
I went back to sleep.

26:14.506 --> 26:16.303
- Did it wake your parents up?

26:16.374 --> 26:18.467
- No, as far as I know.

26:18.543 --> 26:22.035
The next morning
the detectives were pounding
on the door

26:22.147 --> 26:24.513
and I told them what I had,
you know, experienced.

26:24.583 --> 26:26.016
- Yeah.

26:26.084 --> 26:28.678
- Do you think you were
1 of the 38

26:28.753 --> 26:31.881
that were reported
to have done nothing?

26:31.990 --> 26:34.015
- I -- I supposed I could be

26:34.092 --> 26:35.889
I could be counted
in with that.

26:35.994 --> 26:37.086
-Hmm.
When the police --

26:37.162 --> 26:38.686
- Because I woke up

26:38.763 --> 26:43.530
I looked out the window...
and I went back to bed.

26:45.103 --> 26:48.300
But I wasn't in that group.
-Yeah.

26:48.406 --> 26:51.239
- I -- I, that was not my
behavior in that, in that.

26:51.343 --> 26:52.867
-Yeah.
- Yeah.

26:52.944 --> 26:56.436
- In my research, your name
and your mom's name

26:56.548 --> 26:58.311
is down there as saying

26:58.383 --> 27:02.012
"I heard, George, he's --"
Eh, let me get it right

27:02.087 --> 27:04.578
"George, he's, he's done it
to me.

27:04.689 --> 27:07.283
George, he's done it to me."
Twice.

27:07.359 --> 27:09.884
And then, "Please help me."

27:09.961 --> 27:11.986
So, you and your mom

27:12.097 --> 27:15.726
you were probably counted
as part of the 38.

27:17.302 --> 27:19.770
And, according
to your remembering

27:19.871 --> 27:22.669
your mom never said anything?

27:22.741 --> 27:25.710
- No, as far as I know, she
never spoke to the police
at all.

27:25.777 --> 27:27.244
-Yeah.

27:27.312 --> 27:29.075
-Wow, I have no idea
who George is

27:29.147 --> 27:33.811
but I, I never heard
of anything like that.

27:33.918 --> 27:36.409
And as far as I know
momma was asleep.

27:36.488 --> 27:37.648
That is shocking.

27:39.457 --> 27:40.481
Wow.

27:42.394 --> 27:44.259
[instrumental music]

27:46.598 --> 27:47.724
[knocks on the door]

27:49.834 --> 27:51.768
- Come on in.
- Hello.

27:51.836 --> 27:54.134
- How are ya?
- You're Hattie?

27:54.239 --> 27:55.831
- Yes.
- Hi, Bill Genovese.

27:55.907 --> 27:57.374
- Nice to meet you.
- How're you doing?

27:57.442 --> 27:58.409
- Nice strong grip.

28:00.779 --> 28:02.974
-Were you ever interviewed
by the police?

28:03.081 --> 28:05.242
- Yes, I think I was, yeah.

28:05.316 --> 28:08.410
- This is what they recorded
anyway, that you said to them.

28:08.486 --> 28:12.115
"Hattie Grund, saw a woman
screaming, "Help."

28:12.190 --> 28:15.455
"She was standing
in front of cleaners.
No male was present."

28:15.527 --> 28:21.056
- That's true. I heard somebody
saying "Help, help.."

28:21.166 --> 28:24.795
...from what I recall
and then I called the police.

28:24.869 --> 28:26.359
- You called the police?
-Always.

28:26.471 --> 28:30.498
And they said,
"We already got the calls."

28:30.608 --> 28:33.543
- Hmm.
-I didn't even finish
my statement.

28:33.611 --> 28:37.206
And they said,
"We've already gotten the call."

28:37.282 --> 28:39.113
It wasn't that people
didn't call.

28:39.184 --> 28:42.449
There might have been other
people that called..

28:42.520 --> 28:45.683
...because once you got
the police station

28:45.790 --> 28:49.624
before you could finish they
said, "We've gotten the calls."

28:49.694 --> 28:53.528
- When news reporters, uh,
came to talk to you, uh

28:53.631 --> 28:57.123
were they pushing the, you
know, the witness story
and asking --

28:57.202 --> 29:00.638
- Oh yeah, they were persistent
in getting information,
you know.

29:00.705 --> 29:04.141
And that's the thing Kew Gardens
got a little aroused

29:04.209 --> 29:06.700
when they said they were,
we were apathetic.

29:09.347 --> 29:12.282
We were not. There are always
a few people that call.

29:17.422 --> 29:19.754
[instrumental music]

29:19.858 --> 29:21.621
-After hearing
Hattie Grund claim

29:21.693 --> 29:23.684
she and others
called the police.

29:23.762 --> 29:28.062
I requested the police log
of phone calls
from that night.

29:28.166 --> 29:30.760
The only call they list
is from Karl Ross

29:30.835 --> 29:32.632
well after Moseley was gone.

29:34.339 --> 29:37.331
Did the police fail
to log the calls?

29:37.408 --> 29:40.571
Or did Hattie just create
a story she could live with?

29:43.515 --> 29:45.847
A witness who doesn't know
she's a witness.

29:47.519 --> 29:51.216
So many other missed details
of that night.

29:51.289 --> 29:53.814
Like the fact that Kitty
didn't die alone.

29:56.795 --> 29:59.593
How could anything be believed
about this story?

30:03.735 --> 30:05.100
I never questioned it.

30:06.871 --> 30:08.202
Two years after Kitty's death

30:08.273 --> 30:09.740
I graduated high school.

30:11.276 --> 30:14.609
The Vietnam War
was in full swing.

30:14.712 --> 30:17.306
Many of my peers were looking
for ways not to serve.

30:18.950 --> 30:20.542
Whether the war
was right or wrong

30:20.618 --> 30:21.642
I couldn't help but see them

30:21.753 --> 30:24.722
as apathetic bystanders.

30:24.789 --> 30:27.758
I wasn't going to be like
the 38 witnesses

30:27.826 --> 30:29.760
So I enlisted in the Marines.

30:31.763 --> 30:35.062
And at 18, you're going off
to war and you're thinking

30:35.133 --> 30:36.623
"I'll come home okay."

30:41.472 --> 30:43.337
[music continues]

30:58.523 --> 31:01.356
-I think he's looking
for the ultimate inner peace.

31:01.459 --> 31:03.893
The choices that he made
in his life

31:03.962 --> 31:06.226
um, were all related to the fact

31:06.297 --> 31:09.630
that no one
helped his sister.

31:11.669 --> 31:14.297
And if he knows the truth,
that's a peacefulness.

31:16.507 --> 31:20.136
I mean, I'm hoping for Bill
that there'll be closure.

31:20.211 --> 31:21.542
You know, like he didn't
lose his legs

31:21.646 --> 31:23.170
in Vietnam for nothing.

31:29.120 --> 31:30.985
[music continues]

31:41.332 --> 31:43.994
-The version of the story
that was accepted as fact

31:44.068 --> 31:45.501
for so many years was written

31:45.570 --> 31:48.232
by the late reporter
Martin Gansberg.

31:49.641 --> 31:50.835
His editor at "The Time"

31:50.909 --> 31:53.070
was a man named Abe Rosenthal

31:53.177 --> 31:56.340
who became a major figure
in journalism.

31:56.414 --> 31:58.882
From what I've found,
it's Rosenthal

31:58.983 --> 32:01.577
who's credited with breaking
the story.

32:01.653 --> 32:03.245
And later that year

32:03.321 --> 32:06.085
he wrote a book called
"38 Witnesses."

32:09.928 --> 32:12.795
-This story has never died.

32:12.897 --> 32:15.730
I still get mail about it,
people write theses about it.

32:15.833 --> 32:19.200
There are lectures
and seminars at universities.

32:19.270 --> 32:21.568
They are obsessed
by this story.

32:23.708 --> 32:24.675
It's like a jewel.

32:24.742 --> 32:26.107
You keep looking at it

32:26.210 --> 32:27.802
and different things
occur to you.

32:27.879 --> 32:30.040
It's affected my approach
to life, I think.

32:35.286 --> 32:37.720
-Okay, sir.

32:37.789 --> 32:40.883
-According to his book,
he first heard
my sister's name

32:40.959 --> 32:43.086
when he had lunch
with the city's police chief

32:43.194 --> 32:44.855
10 days after the murder.

32:47.065 --> 32:49.431
- I was, uh, nauseated
at the idea

32:49.534 --> 32:51.525
that people in New York City

32:51.602 --> 32:54.901
in Queens, knew that a girl
was getting killed.

32:54.973 --> 32:57.066
And later they dis,
it was discovered

32:57.141 --> 33:01.805
that 38 people
didn't do anything.

33:01.913 --> 33:05.576
It was the failure
of New York City

33:05.650 --> 33:07.618
or the people
of New York City

33:07.719 --> 33:10.984
to take action, stick out
a hand, do something.

33:11.055 --> 33:14.752
- Right.
- Shout, "Hey, we need help."

33:14.826 --> 33:18.694
And that was what grabbed
the people of the city

33:18.796 --> 33:20.161
and other cities.

33:20.264 --> 33:22.255
- Well, where did
the number 38 come?

33:22.333 --> 33:26.667
I wonder was it synthesized
somehow to make a big impact?
- No.

33:26.771 --> 33:28.136
-So that we could
get a positive.

33:28.239 --> 33:29.729
I mean,
for a positive result --

33:29.807 --> 33:31.502
- You asked the question
and I'm telling you.

33:31.609 --> 33:34.134
I can't swear to God

33:34.245 --> 33:36.338
that there were 38 people.

33:36.414 --> 33:37.438
Some people say
there were more

33:37.515 --> 33:39.039
some people say
there were less

33:39.150 --> 33:41.118
but what was true..

33:41.185 --> 33:44.052
...people all over the world

33:44.155 --> 33:45.782
were affected by it.

33:45.857 --> 33:47.518
Did it do anything?

33:47.625 --> 33:50.150
You bet your eye
it did something.

33:50.261 --> 33:52.354
And I'm glad it did.

33:56.267 --> 33:58.132
[instrumental music]

34:00.838 --> 34:03.136
-Forty years after
the original article appeared

34:03.207 --> 34:06.574
the "New York Times"
reexamined their account.

34:06.677 --> 34:10.168
They acknowledged
some of the original
article's flaws

34:10.281 --> 34:13.909
and highlighted the questions
surrounding the story.

34:13.985 --> 34:15.976
Most of the revisionist
information

34:16.054 --> 34:17.987
came from Joe DeMay.

34:18.056 --> 34:21.514
A Kew Gardens resident
and amateur historian.

34:21.626 --> 34:24.958
- I sat down and I read
through the article

34:25.029 --> 34:27.054
and when it was all through
I thought to myself

34:27.165 --> 34:28.655
"What the heck this,
this can't make

34:28.733 --> 34:30.257
this doesn't make
any sense at all."

34:30.368 --> 34:32.699
If you read
through the article

34:32.804 --> 34:34.567
the first paragraph
is crystal clear

34:34.639 --> 34:35.628
and absolutely riveting.

34:36.808 --> 34:38.435
For more than half an hour

34:38.509 --> 34:40.500
38 respectable,
law-abiding citizens

34:40.578 --> 34:42.773
in Queens watched
a killer stalk
and stab a woman

34:42.880 --> 34:46.007
in 3 separate attacks
in Kew Gardens.

34:46.083 --> 34:49.349
Well, turns out there weren't
38 eyewitnesses at all.

34:49.420 --> 34:52.081
The witnesses to the case,
with one or two exceptions

34:52.190 --> 34:55.523
were ear witnesses,
not eye witnesses.

34:55.592 --> 34:57.288
What happened is this.

34:57.395 --> 35:00.364
There was an initial attack
on Austin Street

35:00.431 --> 35:03.093
that was broken off,
the killer fled.

35:03.201 --> 35:04.896
Your sister then got up
and she walked around

35:05.002 --> 35:06.697
to the back of the building.

35:06.771 --> 35:08.864
The people in the apartment
building could not

35:08.940 --> 35:12.603
have seen her for more
than a couple of minutes.

35:12.710 --> 35:14.541
When they saw him come back
the few witnesses

35:14.612 --> 35:16.443
that were still at their
windows, Kitty was long gone

35:16.547 --> 35:18.981
as far as they knew
she was some place safe.

35:19.050 --> 35:22.679
So, yeah, the story
was generally correct

35:22.753 --> 35:24.721
but in a lot of the important
details it was grossly

35:24.789 --> 35:26.916
exaggerated and simply
not true.

35:32.697 --> 35:34.858
-When I first came upon
his website

35:34.932 --> 35:37.400
my first reaction
was to sort of brush it off.

35:37.468 --> 35:39.402
But then I came back
and read it very closely

35:39.470 --> 35:43.839
and realized, "Wow, his argument
is incredibly compelling."

35:43.941 --> 35:46.705
If the story had been reported
more accurately

35:46.777 --> 35:48.870
it still would have been
a 2 or 3 day

35:48.946 --> 35:50.743
maybe -- maybe even 4 day story

35:50.815 --> 35:53.306
but it would not have been
a 50 year story.

35:53.417 --> 35:56.250
We would not still be sitting
here talking about it today.

35:56.320 --> 35:59.255
- Did anybody ever challenge
the 38 witness

35:59.323 --> 36:01.689
38 eyewitness story?

36:01.792 --> 36:03.817
- Yeah. Not at the time.

36:03.928 --> 36:07.420
Not in 1964.
In fact to the contrary.

36:07.498 --> 36:11.798
Other newspapers, other
magazines, "Li-Life Magazine"

36:11.903 --> 36:14.701
ran with it and then even
exaggerated it further.

36:18.676 --> 36:20.200
-This is Mike Wallace.

36:20.311 --> 36:23.747
Why did 38 people fail to act?

36:23.814 --> 36:26.180
The answer to that question
concerns every one of us

36:26.284 --> 36:29.082
who fears perhaps that apathy

36:29.153 --> 36:31.678
has become part
of our way of life.

36:31.789 --> 36:33.450
-The question becomes

36:33.524 --> 36:35.890
was it worth
all the attention it got

36:35.993 --> 36:39.258
or was it a media creation?

36:39.330 --> 36:44.427
- Oh, I think to a certain
degree it was a media creation.

36:44.502 --> 36:47.164
No one investigated the 38.

36:47.271 --> 36:50.707
No one followed up on it
or anything of that nature.

36:50.775 --> 36:53.141
- Do you have any feel
for why that would have been

36:53.211 --> 36:57.511
with this case
versus any other case?

36:57.615 --> 36:59.139
- Because it was taken
seriously

36:59.217 --> 37:00.684
by "The New York Times."

37:02.520 --> 37:04.488
The reason I picked up on it..

37:04.555 --> 37:09.583
...was because Abe Rosenthal
is a man I respect.

37:09.694 --> 37:12.891
Good reporter, in a position
of authority

37:12.997 --> 37:14.988
at "The New York Times."

37:15.066 --> 37:19.867
I mean, "The Times" had, still
does, but back then particularly

37:19.971 --> 37:21.962
had that kind of clout.

37:22.039 --> 37:26.408
It's a fascinating...
troubling story.

37:30.915 --> 37:34.715
And undoubtedly,
sold newspapers.

37:34.819 --> 37:37.811
- Hi, is this Mr. Lelyveld?
-Yes, sir.

37:37.888 --> 37:40.015
-When did you start working
at "The Times? "

37:40.091 --> 37:43.720
-I became a reporter
in 1963, I guess.

37:43.828 --> 37:47.093
- Do you think the original
"Times" story is accurate?

37:47.164 --> 37:50.429
-I remember feeling
it was a little skimpy.
- Yeah.

37:50.501 --> 37:53.527
-That it, that it reached
its judgment quickly.

37:53.604 --> 37:56.368
- Have you ever heard
of a woman named Sophia Farrar?

37:56.440 --> 37:57.429
-No.

37:57.541 --> 37:59.008
-Sophia Farrar actually did

37:59.076 --> 38:00.509
go down to be with her

38:00.578 --> 38:02.239
as soon as she found out
about it.

38:02.346 --> 38:04.143
-And did the police list her

38:04.215 --> 38:05.648
as a witness in their reports?

38:05.716 --> 38:08.207
- Yeah, she testified in court.

38:08.286 --> 38:10.083
-And she's not mentioned
in "The Times" story?

38:10.187 --> 38:11.154
- No.

38:11.222 --> 38:12.189
-Well, that's just, uh

38:12.256 --> 38:13.780
that's inexcusable then.

38:13.891 --> 38:15.518
The question would be
why the competition

38:15.593 --> 38:17.561
didn't look into it.

38:17.628 --> 38:19.459
- Hi, Richard Wald?
-Speaking.

38:19.563 --> 38:21.258
-You were the managing editor

38:21.365 --> 38:25.665
at "The New York Herald
Tribune" in '64?

38:25.736 --> 38:27.931
Did "The Tribune"
ever write a story

38:28.039 --> 38:30.974
about how "The Times"
covered the story of 38?

38:31.042 --> 38:34.307
-No, I don't remember
"The Tribune" ever doing that.

38:34.378 --> 38:36.869
Let's assume you were
a reporter on the scene.

38:36.947 --> 38:38.972
If you had a sense
that it didn't happen

38:39.083 --> 38:42.018
that way,
I would have assigned people
to go and check.

38:42.086 --> 38:43.383
- Right.

38:43.454 --> 38:44.478
-But I don't know
any reporter

38:44.588 --> 38:46.112
who felt that way.

38:49.927 --> 38:51.918
- Mr. Pressman.
- Hi, Bill. How are you?

38:51.996 --> 38:53.429
- Good. I'm good.

38:53.497 --> 38:57.934
-In 1964,
I was a reporter at WNBC

38:58.002 --> 39:01.335
and I had no first hand
knowledge of the story

39:01.439 --> 39:04.135
but my friend Danny Meenan
covered the story.

39:04.241 --> 39:06.232
At this point
he was doing radio

39:06.310 --> 39:10.269
I believe for WMCA,
and, uh

39:10.348 --> 39:12.111
among all the police reporters
I've known

39:12.183 --> 39:14.014
and I've known many,
he was one of the best

39:14.118 --> 39:16.416
if not the best.

39:16.487 --> 39:19.285
He said, "The story doesn't make
any sense to me."

39:19.357 --> 39:21.825
And he gave me an account of

39:21.926 --> 39:25.418
uh, what he found.

39:25.496 --> 39:28.522
And it says here,
"There were many witnesses.

39:28.632 --> 39:31.066
"Some 30 odd in the number.

39:31.135 --> 39:34.571
"One conclusion all seemed
to have, it was a drunken brawl

39:34.638 --> 39:36.731
between man and wife."

39:36.807 --> 39:38.468
Martin Gansberg, the author

39:38.542 --> 39:40.669
of the "Page One Story"
in "The Times"

39:40.778 --> 39:43.303
which caused the furor,
was challenged

39:43.381 --> 39:47.010
by this irate reporter.

39:47.118 --> 39:49.916
"Why didn't you include
in your story

39:49.987 --> 39:52.080
"the fact that many
witnesses did not

39:52.156 --> 39:55.182
believe a murder
was taking place? "

39:55.292 --> 39:57.590
Gansberg replied..

39:57.661 --> 40:00.152
"...It would have ruined
the story."

40:04.568 --> 40:06.331
-That to me is incredible.

40:08.506 --> 40:11.202
It's curious to me why,

40:11.308 --> 40:14.300
and I'm not trying
to blame Danny Meenan

40:14.378 --> 40:16.869
or yourself or anybody else
but why --

40:16.981 --> 40:20.815
how come people didn't call
"The Times" out on that?

40:20.885 --> 40:23.046
- Because it was
"The New York Times"

40:23.154 --> 40:25.418
and Danny, you know,

40:25.489 --> 40:28.515
he had to continue
to hold on to his job.

40:28.592 --> 40:30.219
I don't think that he
probably was interested

40:30.327 --> 40:33.854
in taking on Abe Rosenthal
and "The New York Times."

40:33.931 --> 40:36.024
A couple of years passed,

40:36.100 --> 40:38.068
I was teaching a course

40:38.169 --> 40:39.693
and this seemed
to be something

40:39.770 --> 40:42.466
that the class
would want to explore.

40:42.573 --> 40:45.872
A couple of the people
in my class being enterprising

40:45.943 --> 40:48.468
I guess you would say,
called Rosenthal.

40:49.513 --> 40:53.040
And Rosenthal called me.

40:53.117 --> 40:55.779
He was really angry,
he was screaming at me.

40:55.886 --> 40:57.683
"Do you realize," said Rosenthal

40:57.755 --> 41:00.588
"that this story has become

41:00.691 --> 41:03.990
emblematic of a situation
in America? "

41:04.061 --> 41:07.553
"That it's become the subject
of sociology courses

41:07.631 --> 41:09.826
books and articles."

41:09.934 --> 41:12.732
And I think that
that is abhorrent

41:12.803 --> 41:16.000
to anyone
who is interested in truth.

41:18.809 --> 41:20.640
-For me to hear that,
it's just shocking

41:20.744 --> 41:24.236
because I grew up and moved
in certain directions

41:24.315 --> 41:28.012
based on this story
being fact.

41:28.118 --> 41:31.747
But indeed it was
not totally fact.

41:35.593 --> 41:37.959
- Did they say why they just
sat there doing nothing

41:38.062 --> 41:40.496
while that girl
screamed for help?

41:40.564 --> 41:42.657
- They all had
the same answer.

41:42.733 --> 41:44.826
They didn't wanna get involved.

41:44.902 --> 41:46.563
- A young woman
stabbed 14 times

41:46.637 --> 41:48.161
then raped
outside her building.

41:48.272 --> 41:50.297
- While 40 of her neighbors
turned up their TVs

41:50.407 --> 41:52.534
so they couldn't
hear the screams.

41:52.610 --> 41:54.976
- If you're a witness
in one of these things,
you know what you gotta do?

41:55.079 --> 41:56.944
Put on a shirt and tie,
you gotta go down to court --

41:57.014 --> 41:58.003
- So because of a little
inconvenience

41:58.115 --> 41:59.742
you don't wanna get involved?!

41:59.817 --> 42:01.614
- Listen, let me explain
something to you, huh?

42:01.685 --> 42:03.653
Shut up!

42:05.956 --> 42:07.423
-You look at things
that happen in the world

42:07.491 --> 42:10.119
and that's one of the ways
that you decide

42:10.194 --> 42:11.991
what course
you're gonna take.

42:12.096 --> 42:13.688
And if those things
aren't accurate

42:13.764 --> 42:17.131
then you could
chart the wrong course.

42:17.201 --> 42:20.295
If Kitty Genovese

42:20.371 --> 42:22.532
is a name
that immediately summons

42:22.640 --> 42:24.335
something to people's minds

42:24.441 --> 42:27.774
then that thing that gets
summoned should be the truth.

42:33.050 --> 42:34.984
[birds chirping]

42:35.052 --> 42:36.485
- So, that's everyone who,
who saw --

42:36.554 --> 42:38.351
-These are witnesses.

42:38.455 --> 42:41.219
-Witnessed in some way,
at least heard something.

42:41.292 --> 42:45.456
And A.M. Rosenthal's the guy
who wrote "38 Witnesses."
- Right.

42:45.529 --> 42:48.054
-The truth of the matter is,
38 people didn't see it.

42:48.165 --> 42:49.792
- Okay.

42:49.867 --> 42:53.200
Dr. and Mrs. Rubenstein
heard screams, "Help, help

42:53.304 --> 42:54.566
they're killing me."

42:54.638 --> 42:56.265
-You know, I often wondered

42:56.340 --> 42:58.865
how much detail
Billy would get into.

42:58.976 --> 43:01.809
- "He heard a woman scream
at about 3 o'clock."

43:01.879 --> 43:04.313
-So and so did this,
so and so opened the window,

43:04.381 --> 43:08.249
so and so shouted,
so and so --

43:08.352 --> 43:11.344
For what? She's dead.

43:11.422 --> 43:15.882
She's murdered,
you know.

43:15.993 --> 43:18.791
I don't want --
Why do I wanna hear that?

43:18.862 --> 43:22.696
- "Standing over her
and repeatedly striking her.
The girl then --"

43:22.766 --> 43:26.202
-I personally never heard
a story

43:26.270 --> 43:29.296
from my dad's family members
about Kitty.

43:29.406 --> 43:33.365
I think her death
overshadowed her life

43:33.444 --> 43:37.278
for anybody involved with it.

43:37.381 --> 43:39.906
- In some ways there was this
hush-hush about her life

43:40.017 --> 43:42.451
because they couldn't talk
about her death.

43:42.519 --> 43:44.214
It probably made it
more traumatic

43:44.288 --> 43:46.950
because they weren't able
to celebrate her life.

43:47.057 --> 43:49.252
They were focusing
on her death
by hiding the fact

43:49.360 --> 43:50.725
that she was even alive
to begin with.

43:52.630 --> 43:55.793
-I mean, to me,
she's a picture in a magazine.

43:55.899 --> 44:00.233
I know her from things
I read on Wikipedia

44:00.304 --> 44:04.240
or Googled or read randomly
in a book

44:04.308 --> 44:06.469
when I was in high school
in English class

44:06.577 --> 44:07.839
and didn't realize
it was my aunt

44:07.911 --> 44:09.378
until about half-way through.

44:09.446 --> 44:10.913
I know how she died.
- Yeah.

44:10.981 --> 44:12.243
- That's the story
I could tell you.

44:19.590 --> 44:21.387
-Inside, dad?
- Yeah.

44:21.458 --> 44:23.653
[engine whirring]

44:37.341 --> 44:40.538
One more.

44:40.644 --> 44:42.839
As you're beating your head up
against the wall

44:42.946 --> 44:45.437
and having to relive
this murder scene

44:45.516 --> 44:48.110
over and over again, it's like,
you know, you stop and say

44:48.185 --> 44:49.516
"Why the hell
am I doing this?

44:49.620 --> 44:51.815
This is, like, nuts.

44:51.922 --> 44:54.049
I don't know, I guess
the message for me

44:54.124 --> 44:57.287
and why I can't stop until
I feel like it's over.

44:57.361 --> 44:58.555
-Yeah, when is it over?

44:58.662 --> 45:00.254
- I -- I'll know
when it's over.

45:02.633 --> 45:04.794
Let me just describe something
really quickly.

45:04.868 --> 45:06.995
My sister Kitty, for you,
would be

45:07.104 --> 45:09.072
a combination of mom and me.

45:11.141 --> 45:13.473
So imagine that.

45:13.544 --> 45:15.671
Mom and I both get murdered
on the street.

45:21.685 --> 45:24.210
- Well, see, I never knew
it was like that for you.

45:24.321 --> 45:25.686
Like, you've never --

45:25.789 --> 45:28.383
I mean, you've never expressed
it in that way.

45:29.460 --> 45:30.791
- Right.

45:35.999 --> 45:37.626
So the obsessive part of me

45:37.701 --> 45:38.963
that's gotta get
to the end of it

45:39.036 --> 45:40.526
the end isn't reached yet.

45:40.637 --> 45:43.299
There's see -- there's more
bases I'd like to touch.

45:43.373 --> 45:47.173
For instance, like, Kitty
was married, did you know that?

45:47.244 --> 45:49.405
- No, I --
No.

45:54.852 --> 45:57.218
[instrumental music]

46:08.899 --> 46:11.868
-My sister was so much more
than her final 30 minutes.

46:13.771 --> 46:15.261
But in our late-night talks,

46:15.372 --> 46:17.636
her life in the city
barely came up.

46:20.110 --> 46:22.203
All I knew was
she worked in a bar.

46:22.279 --> 46:25.271
Was briefly married
to a man named Rocco.

46:28.352 --> 46:30.843
In the past few years,
journalists have revealed

46:30.921 --> 46:33.856
that her roommate Mary Ann
was actually her lover.

46:36.560 --> 46:38.755
If I didn't know something
as important as that

46:38.862 --> 46:41.057
how well did I really
know my sister?

46:43.901 --> 46:46.199
Even though I haven't seen him
since I was 6

46:46.270 --> 46:48.261
I decided to reach out
to Rocco.

46:51.441 --> 46:54.308
"Dear Rocco, I've been working
with a filmmaker

46:54.411 --> 46:58.507
for several years
on a documentary about Kitty."

46:58.582 --> 47:00.846
"At this point, I have
questions about her life

47:00.918 --> 47:03.443
"in New York
after high school

47:03.554 --> 47:06.045
and I think you hold the key
to the answers."

47:08.292 --> 47:12.126
"William, I respect
the feeling expressed
in your message

47:12.229 --> 47:14.493
"and I ask you do the same
for mine

47:14.565 --> 47:17.329
which are to respect
my desire for privacy."

47:19.303 --> 47:22.568
"My relations with Kitty shall
remain a mystery forever."

47:25.342 --> 47:27.333
[instrumental music]

47:29.980 --> 47:31.743
-Hi, pops.

47:33.083 --> 47:35.449
What are you doing?

47:35.519 --> 47:38.784
- I'm reading through
Kitty's yearbook.

47:38.856 --> 47:42.724
"May we dance forever
on each others' feet"

47:42.826 --> 47:45.192
Love and Stuff, Elsa."

47:49.533 --> 47:51.057
So this is where you went
to high school?

47:51.168 --> 47:53.693
-This is where
we went to high school.

47:53.804 --> 47:56.739
And when we played hooky,
we were in that park.

47:56.807 --> 47:57.774
which we did a lot.

48:00.277 --> 48:03.246
-Did Kitty have any
aspirations of going
to college?

48:03.313 --> 48:04.803
-No.

48:04.882 --> 48:07.749
And it's interesting
because she was smart.

48:07.851 --> 48:11.844
But I don't remember her
ever striving for the "A."

48:11.955 --> 48:14.822
Probably 'cause
we were all cut-ups.

48:14.892 --> 48:17.690
[upbeat music]

48:17.794 --> 48:20.319
Everyone loved Kitty.

48:20.397 --> 48:22.388
She was funny, very witty.

48:24.868 --> 48:26.893
She had an, an enormous
following.

48:30.073 --> 48:32.541
[music continues]

48:35.245 --> 48:38.681
She was a very good mimic
of teachers

48:38.749 --> 48:40.182
particularly
our French teacher.

48:40.250 --> 48:41.842
She would do
the Sid Caesar thing

48:41.919 --> 48:43.580
where she made believe
she was talking French.

48:43.687 --> 48:46.155
[speaking in French]

48:48.492 --> 48:49.857
[music continues]

48:49.927 --> 48:52.623
To be in Kitty's clique
was a big deal.

48:53.997 --> 48:55.487
We played hooky.

48:57.067 --> 48:59.661
We went to the beach

48:59.736 --> 49:01.169
or here in the park

49:01.238 --> 49:03.706
or smoking on the roof.

49:03.774 --> 49:05.799
And she was the head
of the pack.

49:11.882 --> 49:14.976
-So, you first heard
about Kitty's murder --

49:15.052 --> 49:17.247
- I remember reading the obit.

49:17.354 --> 49:21.017
It said that she was a barmaid.
-Yeah.

49:21.091 --> 49:22.058
- Okay?

49:22.125 --> 49:25.561
And, um, I was, I --

49:25.629 --> 49:28.723
I remember thinking,
"What a pity, what a waste"

49:28.799 --> 49:31.097
that she wound up a barmaid.

49:33.971 --> 49:36.804
- I'm Wally Brosnan, Bill.
- Wally, Bill Genovese.

49:36.907 --> 49:38.568
I was a friend
of Kitty's, too.

49:38.642 --> 49:40.769
- Good. Nice to meet you.
- Hiya, Bill.

49:40.877 --> 49:42.344
- Nice to meet you.
- My pleasure.

49:42.412 --> 49:44.346
-Kitty started out
as a bar maid

49:44.414 --> 49:48.350
but eventually she earned
a position as a bar manager.

49:48.418 --> 49:52.377
Her last job was at a tavern
called "Ev's 11th Hour."

49:52.456 --> 49:53.889
Somehow I didn't
imagine this.

49:53.957 --> 49:55.447
The neighborhood's
changed quite a bit.

49:55.559 --> 49:57.925
- Neither did we.
We didn't imagine it either.

49:57.995 --> 49:59.360
- Big difference.

50:01.164 --> 50:02.654
-When did the bar open?

50:02.766 --> 50:04.563
- 8 o'clock in the morning.

50:04.634 --> 50:06.295
- Now, you better
be here at 8:00.

50:06.403 --> 50:08.837
Or else they'll be
knocking down the door.

50:08.905 --> 50:11.738
- Well, what was she like
in there, was she, you know

50:11.808 --> 50:14.140
if there was trouble, did --
did anybody get into fights?

50:14.244 --> 50:17.270
- She cut off what's his name,
Harry Allerman

50:17.347 --> 50:19.645
she cut him off, told him
he couldn't come in anymore.

50:19.750 --> 50:21.081
- Why, what was he doing,
screamin', yellin'?

50:21.151 --> 50:23.312
- Well, you know,
he was just a drunk.

50:23.420 --> 50:24.785
- So would you, would you --

50:24.855 --> 50:26.447
Was she like a tough person
to deal with?

50:26.523 --> 50:29.549
- No!
- She was a pussycat.

50:29.659 --> 50:31.422
-When, uh, when my
last daughter was born

50:31.495 --> 50:33.292
she came to the hospital
with me.

50:33.363 --> 50:34.694
-Oh, really?
- Yeah.

50:34.798 --> 50:36.789
Yeah, she came
to the hospital with me.

50:36.867 --> 50:38.801
-She was just --
she was just good

50:38.869 --> 50:40.666
like, she'd goof with ya.

50:40.771 --> 50:43.706
You know, you'd goof with her
and she -- right back at you

50:43.774 --> 50:46.242
you know, right back at you.

50:46.309 --> 50:47.776
-What was Ev's bar like?

50:47.844 --> 50:51.280
- Uh, it was like,
uh, cheers.

50:51.348 --> 50:54.146
Everybody knows everybody else
and everybody's business.

50:54.217 --> 50:55.809
-Do you think she liked
working there?

50:55.886 --> 50:57.353
- Oh, she loved it. Yeah.
-Yeah?

50:57.454 --> 50:59.922
- Oh, yeah.
That bar was her home.

50:59.990 --> 51:02.151
She was the queen
of the place.

51:02.225 --> 51:05.888
Some of the people at the bar
used to think I was her
boyfriend.

51:05.996 --> 51:07.258
But I don't think
the people at the bar

51:07.330 --> 51:08.456
had any idea she was gay.

51:08.532 --> 51:10.329
- Hmm.

51:10.400 --> 51:13.392
- I don't, in fact,
I'm positive they didn't
know about it.

51:13.503 --> 51:16.597
- Oh, yeah. Everybody
knew that she was gay.

51:16.673 --> 51:18.937
- Oh, really?
-Oh, yeah. Everybody knew.

51:19.009 --> 51:21.842
And let's put it this way,
she was one of the boys.

51:21.912 --> 51:24.506
I mean, guys used to borrow
money off her.

51:24.581 --> 51:26.572
- Borrow money from her?
-Yeah.

51:26.683 --> 51:31.552
Everybody in there gambled
in one way or another.

51:31.655 --> 51:34.317
- Kitty was arrested
for something

51:34.391 --> 51:35.358
or charged with something.

51:35.425 --> 51:37.017
What was that about?

51:37.094 --> 51:38.459
- Not that I knew of.

51:38.562 --> 51:39.756
-What do you guys
know about that?

51:39.863 --> 51:42.491
- No, I don't,
I don't remember that.

51:42.566 --> 51:44.090
-What she would do

51:44.201 --> 51:46.726
people would give her bets
to give to the bookie.

51:46.837 --> 51:47.997
- Hmm.

51:48.071 --> 51:49.595
And she got caught
in the middle.

51:49.706 --> 51:51.401
People were giving
her bets and they said

51:51.508 --> 51:53.203
"You're booking the horses."
That's, that's what happened.

51:53.276 --> 51:56.768
She got locked up or something
for that one time. Yeah.

51:56.880 --> 51:59.075
- I didn't know my sister
was such a racketeer.

51:59.182 --> 52:00.376
[laughing]

52:00.450 --> 52:03.112
[instrumental music]

52:03.220 --> 52:05.381
-Apparently,
Kitty's arrest is the source

52:05.455 --> 52:07.616
of the most famous
picture of her.

52:07.724 --> 52:11.660
For years, I wondered
where did this image
come from?

